	abstract = {A technique is described for accurately controlling the soil moisture régime, in respect of both water availability (suction) and pore size of the soil. With this technique, using aluminium oxide grits as artificial soils, it has been shown that neither suction, in the range 1–600 cm. water, nor pore size, in the range 2·5–130 μ radius of pore-necks, taken as separate factors, restricts hyphal growth of Curvularia ramosa. Similarly, sporulation of this fungus appears to be unaffected by the suctions used but its intensity is severely diminished when the equivalent radius of the pores is reduced to 23μ or less (length of conidium is ca. 27μ.). Measurements of growth rate and observations on the morphology of C. ramosa show that growth is reduced and abnormal in grits with water-filled pores but that it is normal if the grits are drained and the pores are air-filled. It is suggested that the inhibitory effect of water-logging is due to reduced gaseous exchange.},
